üöÄ Master Kubernetes Cluster Management with Kops!

Kubernetes is the gold standard for container orchestration ‚Äî but setting up and managing a production-ready cluster can be complex. That's where Kops (Kubernetes Operations) comes in.

‚öôÔ∏è What is Kops?
Kops is a powerful open-source CLI tool that automates the entire Kubernetes cluster lifecycle ‚Äî from creation to upgrades and teardown ‚Äî with a focus on AWS.

Whether you're deploying for development or production, Kops gives you:
‚úÖ Automated cluster provisioning
‚úÖ High availability configurations
‚úÖ Rolling updates & version upgrades
‚úÖ YAML-driven infrastructure-as-code
‚úÖ Built-in support for add-ons (CNI, monitoring, logging)

üöß Step-by-Step Setup Guide
1Ô∏è Launch EC2 Instance
Use Amazon Linux 2, t2.micro, 20GB disk, with admin IAM permissions.

2Ô∏è Update your PATH
echo 'export PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/bin/' >> ~/.bashrc && source ~/.bashrc

3Ô∏è Install AWS CLI
curl "https://lnkd.in/dbKAjmBt" -o "awscliv2.zip"  
unzip awscliv2.zip && sudo ./aws/install

4Ô∏è Install kubectl
curl -LO "https://lnkd.in/dHhsR6q8"  
chmod +x kubectl && sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

5Ô∏è Install Kops
wget https://lnkd.in/dvEDFreP  
chmod +x kops-linux-amd64 && sudo mv kops-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/kops
6
Ô∏è Verify Tools
kubectl version  
kops version

7Ô∏è Create an S3 Bucket & Enable Versioning
aws s3 mb s3://your-bucket-name
# Turn on versioning in AWS console for data recovery

8Ô∏è Set the Kops State Store

 
export KOPS_STATE_STORE=s3://your-bucket-name
9Ô∏è Create a Kubernetes Cluster
kops create cluster \
 --name yourcluster.k8s.local \
 --zones us-east-1a \
 --master-size t2.medium \
 --master-count 1 \
 --node-size t2.micro \
 --node-count 2 \
 --master-volume-size 20 \
 --node-volume-size 20

üîü Apply the Configuration
kops update cluster --name yourcluster.k8s.local --yes --admin

üßπ Tear Down When Needed
kops delete cluster --name yourcluster.k8s.local --yes

üí° With Kops, you get a reliable, repeatable, and infrastructure-as-code approach to running Kubernetes clusters in the cloud ‚Äî minus the manual headache.
